AAAAAAAK4o%2FxSi_koWUDRE8gt7XsmfwzLZ2Oc88KGtKwCLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i9728!8i4864!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1!6m1!1e1 Broadway - Seventh Avenue Line downtown platform]\n{{refend}}\n\n'''Other websites'''\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* MTA's [[YouTube]] Web Page \u2013 [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WhxfZ0LabbE Advertising Initiatives 9/21/2010] on the 42nd Street (S) Shuttle. Retrieved September 22, 2010. (2:13 video clip)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MelBbmdcSQQ NYCTA Subway Station Tour: 42nd Street\u2013Port Authority/Times Square]\n* Forgotten NY \u2013 [http://forgotten-ny.com/2006/01/the-original-28-part-2-a-look-at-the-artwork-from-the-nycs-first-28-stations-opened-october-27-1904/ Original 28 - NYC's First 28 Subway Stations]\n* The Subway Nut \u2013 [http://www.subwaynut.com/ct/times_sq_7/index.php Times Square\u201342nd Street (7) pictures]\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|l0=y|l1=y|l2=y|l3=y|l7=y|l7x=y|la=y|lc=y|le=y|ln=y|lq=y|lr=y|lw=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|flushing=yes|broadway=yes|42st=yes|8ave=yes|7ave=yes}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Times Square-42nd Street Port Authority Bus Terminal (New York City Subway)}}\n\n[[Category:42nd Street (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:BMT Broadway Line stations]]\n[[Category:Broadway (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:Eighth Avenue (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:IND Eighth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:IRT 42nd Street Shuttle stations]]\n[[Category:IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:IRT Flushing Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway terminals]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway transfer stations]]\n[[Category:Railway and subway stations on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Seventh Avenue (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:Times Square]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Times Square Station}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station complex in Manhattan}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = Times Square\u201342 Street/<br/>&nbsp;Port Authority Bus Terminal\n| type = complex\n| image = Times Square-42nd Street Entrance.JPG\n| image_caption = Entrance to the station at 42nd Street & 7th Avenue\n| bg_color = black\n| accessible = part\n| acc_note = all lines except 42nd Street Shuttle; passageway between IND platforms and rest of complex is not accessible\n| service = Times Square PABT\n| service_header = Times Square PABT header\n| division = BMT/IND/IRT\n| line = {{color box|#{{NYCS color|shuttle}}}}&nbsp;&nbsp;[[42nd Street Shuttle]]<br>{{color box|#{{NYCS color|yellow}}}}&nbsp;&nbsp;[[BMT Broadway Line]]<br>{{color box|#{{NYCS color|red}}}}&nbsp;&nbsp;[[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]]<br>{{color box|#{{NYCS color|blue}}}}&nbsp;&nbsp;[[IND Eighth Avenue Line]]<br>{{color box|#{{NYCS color|purple}}}}&nbsp;&nbsp;[[IRT Flushing Line]]\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|M7|M20|M34A SBS|M42|M104}}, {{NYC bus link|SIM8|SIM8X|SIM22|SIM25|SIM26|SIM30}}<br>{{bus icon}} '''[[MTA Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|BxM2}}<br>{{bus icon}} '''[[Port Authority Bus Terminal]]''' [[NJ Transit Bus Operations|New Jersey Transit Bus]]''': {{NJ bus link|107|108|111|112|113|114|115|116|117|119|121|122|123|124|125|126|127|128|129|130|131|132|133|135|136|137|138|139|144|145|148|151|153|154|155|156|157|158|159|160|161|162|163|164|165|166|167|168|177|190|191|192|193|194|195|196|197|198|199|308|319|320|321|324|353}}\n| address = West 42nd Street, Broadway, Seventh, &amp; Eighth Avenues<br>New York, NY 10036\n| borough = [[Manhattan]]\n| locale = [[Times Square]], [[Midtown Manhattan]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|45|21.6|N|73|59|13.2|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir=N\n| lon_dir=W\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1917|06|03}}<ref name=34th>''[[The New York Times]]'', Three New Links of the Dual Subway System Opened, June 3, 1917, page 33</ref>\n| passengers = 65,060,656 (complex)<ref name=\"2016-rider\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = 0.4\n| rank = 1\n| structure = Underground\n| levels = 5\n| wifi = yes\n| code = 611\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}\n'''Times Square\u201342nd Street/Port Authority Bus Terminal''' is a [[New York City Subway]] [[metro station|station]] complex located under [[Times Square]] and the [[Port Authority Bus Terminal]], at the intersection of [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]], [[Seventh Avenue (Manhattan)|Seventh]] and [[Eighth Avenue (Manhattan)|Eighth Avenues]], and [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] in [[Midtown Manhattan]]. It is the busiest station complex in the system, serving 64,531,511 passengers in 2016.<ref name=\"2016-rider\"/>\n\nThe complex allows free transfers between the [[42nd Street Shuttle|IRT 42nd Street Shuttle]], the [[BMT Broadway Line]], the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] and the [[IRT Flushing Line]], with a long transfer to the [[IND Eighth Avenue Line]] one block west at 42nd Street\u2013Port Authority Bus Terminal. The complex is served by the:\n\n*[[1 (New York City Subway service)|1]], [[2 (New York City Subway service)|2]], [[3 (New York City Subway service)|3]], [[7 (New York City Subway service)|7]], [[A (New York City Subway service)|A]], [[E (New York City Subway service)|E]], [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]], and [[Q (New York City Subway service)|Q]] trains at all times\n*[[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] train during weekdays\n*[[C (New York City Subway service)|C]], [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]], and [[42nd Street Shuttle]] (S) trains at all times except late nights\n*[[7d (New York City Subway service)|&lt;7&gt;]] trains during rush hours in the peak direction\n\n__TOC__\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Station layout==\n{{NYCS Platform Layout Times Square Station}}\n\nThe [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|IRT]] platforms have been connected to each other as a [[transfer station (transportation)|transfer station]] as the lines opened: first between the 42nd Street Shuttle and the Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line in 1917, then the transfer was incorporated with the Flushing Line in 1927.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/28/nyregion/1904-2004-crossroads-of-the-whirl.html |title=1904-2004; Crossroads of the Whirl |last=Dunlap |first=David W. |date=March 28, 2004 |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331|access-date=December 17, 2016}}</ref> On December 24, 1932, a {{convert|600|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} passageway was opened, connecting the [[IND Eighth Avenue Line]] station and the IRT platforms, with a new entrance at West 41st Street between Seventh Avenue and Eighth Avenue.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The passageway was not located within a fare control, and passengers had to pay an extra fare to transfer between the IND and the IRT station.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1932/12/24/100884849.pdf |title=600-Foot Pedestrian Tunnel, Linking Subways, Opens Today |last= |first= |date=December 24, 1932 |work=The New York Times|access-date=October 10, 2016 |via=}}</ref> The [[List of New York City Subway transfer stations|free transfer]] between the IRT and [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation|BMT]] was added on July 1, 1948.<ref name=\"higher\">''[[The New York Times]]'', [https://www.nytimes.com/1948/06/30/archives/transfer-points-under-higher-fare-board-of-transportation-lists.html Transfer Points Under Higher Fare], June 30, 1948, page 19</ref> The block-long passageway that runs west to the 42nd Street\u2013Port Authority Bus Terminal station on the IND Eighth Avenue Line was reopened within [[fare control]] on December 11, 1988.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/12/12/nyregion/all-aboard-somewhere-for-subway-changes.html |title=All Aboard. . .Somewhere. . .for Subway Changes! |last=Lyall |first=Sarah |date=December 12, 1988 |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331|access-date=July 24, 2016}}</ref>[[File:Times Square station entrance vc.ogv|thumb|Entrance]]\nThis station underwent total reconstruction in stages starting in 1994.<ref name=\":0\" /> Phase 1 rebuilt the Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line platforms with a new mezzanine, stairs, and elevators, and was completed in 2002. Phase 2, finished in 2006, rebuilt the Broadway Line, Flushing Line, and Eighth Avenue Line portions of the station.<ref name=\":0\" /> Phase 3, for the shuttle platforms, has yet to be started<ref name=\":0\" /> but will be funded as part of the 2015\u20132019 MTA Capital Program.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> The reconstruction included a new entryway on the south side of 42nd Street between Seventh Avenue and Broadway, featuring a bright neon and colored glass flashing sign with the train route symbols and the word \"Subway\". The street level [[fare control]] at this site features restored original \"Times Square\" mosaics from the Contract I station walls (now used by the shuttle), and both escalators and stairs lead into the complex. There are also similar renovated entrances on the northwest and southwest corners of Seventh Avenue and 42nd Street, the latter of which has both escalators and [[stairs]], while the former has only stairs.\n\nIn 1999, a [[US$]]44 million renovation of the complex began.<ref name=\":0\" /> The goal was to reduce congestion and improve rider access, comfort and safety by improving visual lines and increasing pedestrian capacity. The main corridor was widened {{convert|15|ft|m}}, and the number of sharp corners reduced; [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA accessibility]] was introduced with [[elevator]]s; new [[escalators]]; and other corridors were widened. The [[mezzanine (architecture)|mezzanine]] above the [[BMT Broadway Line]], formerly a record shop, now features a large oval balcony looking over the trackway and has reduced the sense of claustrophobia described by many riders. In 2004, four unisex stall bathrooms were opened on the mezzanine between the IRT and BMT lines; they are staffed and maintained by employees of the Times Square Alliance, the local [[Business Improvement District]]. The record shop re-opened in 2007 on the south side of the IRT/BMT corridor.<ref>[http://www.gothamist.com/archives/2004/07/23/times_square_toilets.php Review and photos of the Times Square bathrooms] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060317071208/http://www.gothamist.com/archives/2004/07/23/times_square_toilets.php |date=March 17, 2006 }} at [[Gothamist]]</ref>\n\nThe mezzanine has been a major featured spot for subway performers ever since the opening of the station. \"[[Music Under New York]]\" controls the spot, which is located by the escalators, opposite the shuttle to Grand Central. Musicians of all types, from musical saw to a brass band, perform there daily.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\n===Exits===\nExits and entrances are located from two main areas: under Eighth Avenue and under Times Square itself.<ref name=MTAMaps-2015>{{cite web |title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Midtown West |url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/mn/M10_midtown_west_2015.pdf |website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]] |publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] |accessdate=December 11, 2015 |date=2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom the Eighth Avenue portion of the complex:\n* One street stair each to the NW, NE, and SE corners of 8th Avenue and 40th Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* Two underground passageways to Port Authority Bus Terminal<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n** One between 40th and 41st Streets\n** {{access icon}} One between 41st and 42nd Streets\n* One street stair to the NW corner of 8th Avenue and 42nd Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* One stair in building on east side of 8th Avenue north of 42nd Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* Escalator bank in building on south side of 42nd Street east of 8th Avenue<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* One street stair to the SW corner of 8th Avenue and 43rd Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* One street stair each to the NW, SW, and SE corners of 8th Avenue and 44th Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n** {{access icon}} The SW corner entrance also has a wheelchair lift\n\nFrom the Times Square portion of the complex:\n* One stair in building on north side of 42nd Street west of 7th Avenue<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* One stair in building on south side of 42nd Street west of 7th Avenue<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* {{access icon}} Elevator and escalator bank in building on south side of 42nd Street between 7th Avenue and Broadway<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* One street stair at SE corner of Broadway and 42nd Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* One stair in building at NE corner of 7th Avenue and 41st Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* Two street stairs at SE corner of 7th Avenue and 41st Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* Two street stairs at SW corner of Broadway and 41st Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* One stair in building on south side of 40th Street west of 7th Avenue<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* One street stair at SE corner of 7th Avenue and 40th Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n* One street stair each to the NW, NE, SW, and SE corners of Broadway and 40th Street<ref name=MTAMaps-2015/>\n\n=== Relative depths ===\nThe relative depths of the station's platforms are:<ref>{{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?7:2345|IND 8th Avenue|42nd Street-Port Authority Bus Terminal }}</ref>\n\n* [[42nd Street Shuttle|IRT 42nd Street Shuttle]], {{convert|20|ft|m}} below street\n* [[IND Eighth Avenue Line]] (one block west), {{convert|30|ft|m}}\n* [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]], {{convert|40|ft|m}}\n* [[BMT Broadway Line]], {{convert|50|ft|m}}\n* [[IRT Flushing Line]], {{convert|60|ft|m}}\n\n== IRT 42nd Street Shuttle platforms ==\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = Times Square\n| former = 42 Street\n| image = Times Square - 42nd Street - Shuttle Track 1.jpg\n| image_caption = Shuttle platform for track 1\n| bg_color = gray\n| division = IRT\n| line = [[42nd Street Shuttle|IRT 42nd Street Shuttle]]\n| service = 42nd\n| platforms = 3 [[side platform]]s (all connected at west end)\n| tracks = 3\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1904|10|27}}<ref name=145th>''[[The New York Times]]'', [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/10/28/118948832.pdf Our Subway Open: 150,000 Try It], October 28, 1904</ref>\n| code = 468\n| wifi = yes\n| accessible = mc\n| acc_note =\n| opposite_transfer = N/A\n| next_topwest = ''Tracks 1 and 3'': {{NYCS next|terminal=(Terminal)|service=42nd|time=show}}<br>''Track 4'': {{NYCS next|station=50th Street|line=IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line|service=none|time=show}}\n| next_east = {{NYCS next | station=Grand Central | line=IRT 42nd Street Shuttle | service=42nd}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}\n}}\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{Routemap\n|title=Track layout\n|title-bg=#{{NYCS color|S}}\n|title-color=white\n|legend =track\n|map=\nnumN060\n\\\\uSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[50th Street (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|50 St]]\nuENDEa+BSar\\uENDEa+BSar\\uSTR+BSl!~BSa ~~ ~~ ~~ {{BSsplit|Movable pedestrian bridge|over Track 4}}\nuSTR+BSr\\uSTR+BSr\\uSTR+BSl\nuSTRf!~NULge\\uSTRf!~NULge\\uSTRf!~NULge\nuSTR!~MFADEf\\uSTR!~MFADEf\\uSTR!~MFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[Grand Central (IRT 42nd Street Shuttle)|Grand Central]]\n}}\n[[File:Times Square subway station original plan.jpg|thumb|200px|Plan of the original station before reconfiguration]]\n}}\nWhen it first opened on October 27, 1904, '''Times Square''' was a local station on New York City's [[early history of the IRT subway|first subway]]. Times Square itself had recently been renamed (from '''Long Acre Square''') in order to give the new subway station a distinctive name.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barron |first1=James |title=100 Years Ago, an Intersection's New Name: Times Square |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/08/nyregion/100-years-ago-an-intersection-s-new-name-times-square.html |accessdate=28 December 2017 |date=April 8, 2004}}</ref> Three shuttle tracks have served it since 1918; the southbound express track (formerly track 2) was removed and replaced by a temporary wooden platform for access to the original northbound express track (now track 3). The former southbound local platform (serving track 1) still has a vestiges of a doorway to the [[The Knickerbocker Hotel (Manhattan)|Knickerbocker Hotel]], while the northbound local platform (serving track 4) retains a former doorway to the Times Building.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe old local platforms still serve tracks 1 and 4, while the southbound express track was removed and replaced with a platform for track 3. all three platforms connect on the west ([[railroad directions|railroad north]]) side. This walkway crosses track 4, the former northbound local track, on a bridge that can be lifted for the only access to that track. North of the station, track 4 merges into the northbound [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] local track along the original subway alignment, north of the current Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line station.<ref name=\":0\" /> The other three tracks once curved parallel to this. Tracks 1 and 3 now end at [[bumper block]]s at the west end of the platforms. There is no track connection between Track 4 and the other tracks anywhere along the shuttle.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBecause of the curvature on the platforms, [[gap filler]]s are used to bridge the gap between train and platform; however, the gap fillers, which are under the platform rather than flush with the platform, are not suitable for wheelchair passengers, making the shuttle platforms inaccessible to wheelchair users. Passengers who need service to [[Grand Central\u201342nd Street (New York City Subway)|Grand Central]] are told to use the IRT Flushing Line platforms. An underpass that formerly connected the original [[side platform]]s lies between the downtown local track and the other three tracks of the [[BMT Broadway Line]], which runs perpendicular to the shuttle.\n\nTracks 1 and 3 have gap fillers, as they are concave and curve toward the shuttle trains. Track 4 does not have gap fillers because of the convex curve of the platform, curving away from the shuttle trains. Track 4 can barely fit the three {{convert|51.4|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}}<!-- length of [[R62A (New York City Subway car)]] --> cars of the shuttle; it originally ended at a wall but now has a small extension for alighting passengers, so the last pair of doors of the train keep one panel disabled for added safety. Track 3 is the longest platform, at four-and-a-half cars long.\n\n===Renovation===\nThe shuttle platform is the only station in the station complex that does not have ADA-accessibility. Although planning had been completed in 2006, the project was delayed due to a lack of funding.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/170221_1000_Transit.pdf |title=Transit and Bus Committee December 2016 |last= |first= |date=February 21, 2017 |website=mta.info |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=February 21, 2017 |page=199}}</ref>  However, as part of the 2015&ndash;2019 Capital Program, the MTA is scheduling some improvements to make it accessible under the guidelines of the Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990. As part of the program, the 42nd Street Shuttle will become ADA-accessible, and the shuttle will be reconfigured from three tracks to two tracks. A new platform, {{convert|28|ft|m}} wide and located between Tracks 1 and 4, would be built along the section of the shuttle that runs under 42nd Street, which is located within a straight tunnel. The whole project will cost $235.41 million. The Times Square shuttle platform will be extended {{convert|360|ft|m}} east to allow for a second point of entry at Sixth Avenue, with a connection to the [[IND Sixth Avenue Line]] as well a second connection to the IRT Flushing Line via its [[Fifth Avenue station (IRT Flushing Line)|Fifth Avenue station]].<ref name=\":3\"/><ref name=\":4\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/capitaldashboard/allframenew_head.html?PROJNUM=t7041404&PLTYPE=1 |title=T7041404 Reconstruction of Times Square Shuttle - Phase 3 |last= |first= |date= |website=web.mta.info |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n|align=left\n|direction=vertical\n|width=250\n|image1=Times Square Expanded Shuttle platform (49397019841).jpg\n|alt1=Rendering of widened platform at Times Square\n|caption1=Widened platform at Times Square, which will be built during the restoration project\n|image2=Times Square Renovation Blue walls.jpg\n|alt2=A platform and track, with a blue construction wall blocking off the space behind the track\n|caption2=Track 1 platform at the start of construction; Track 3 is blocked off by a blue construction wall\n}}\n\nThe entire Times Square station will be rehabilitated with congestion mitigation measures. A wider stairway would be installed from the shuttle mezzanine to street level, a new control area would be installed at the bottom of the stairway, and 21 columns would be removed. The track connection to the Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line would probably be removed with the elimination of Track 4. The cost of this part of the project is $30 million.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/capital/pdf/CapitalProgram2015-19_WEB%20v4%20FINAL_small.pdf |title=MTA Capital Program 2015-2019 |last= |first= |date=October 28, 2015 |website=mta.info |publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|access-date=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe reconstruction work would be done in conjunction with a second project to add access to the Times Square complex. As part of the project, the eastern platform would be closed to public access, and the exit to 43rd Street was closed, covered over, and turned into an emergency exit starting on October 19, 2019. This entrance would be replaced by a new entrance with a twenty-foot wide stairway covered by a canopy. The staircase would lead from the shuttle mezzanine to street level, blocking portions of the station's original finishes. A new control area would be installed at the bottom of the stairway. To further increase capacity, 21 columns would be eliminated; other columns at the station would be thinned, requiring the underpinning of roof beams; and 142 columns in the concourse area would be relocated away from the car doors. This project would cost $28.93 million.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/hearings/160823/Description-of-Projects-Booklet.pdf |title=METROPOLITAN TRANSPORTATION AUTHORITY (MTA) NOTICE OF PUBLIC HEARING AND DESCRIPTION OF PROJECTS Tuesday, August 23, 2016 4:30 P.M. Request for Federal Financial Assistance Under the Federal Transportation Authorization For Federal Fiscal Year 2017 Capital Improvement Projects |date=July 28, 2016 |website=mta.info |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728080805/http://web.mta.info/mta/news/hearings/160823/Description-of-Projects-Booklet.pdf|archive-date=July 28, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=August 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the northern section of the original west platform wall dating from 1904 would be removed, and Jamestown, OTS, would build elevators connecting the station with an observation deck at [[One Times Square]]. The wall would be broken into sections and moved to the [[New York Transit Museum]] to mitigate the adverse effects of the station renovation. To further mitigate damage done to portions of the original station, certain features would be repaired and restored, including the original southwest platform and control area wall finishes, the original cast iron columns, the ceiling plaster ornamentation, and the cast iron guard rails. In addition, the east platform walls that are located within back-of-house space would continue to be protected. The damaged Knickerbocker marble lintel located at the west platform control area would be replicated. To reference portions of the original tracks located at Tracks 2 and 3, the granite paving for the shuttle platform would be modified with a veneer steel rail. These sixty-foot-long sections would be located on the new platform between Tracks 1 and 4. Finally, a display case or plaque describing the history of the station will be installed underneath the replicated Knickerbocker lintel.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/notices/pdf/Amendment-to-TS-Shuttle-MOA-for-Jamestown.pdf |title=AMENDMENT TO THE MEMORANDUM OF AGREEMENT BETWEEN FEDERAL TRANSIT ADMINISTRATION NEW YORK STATE HISTORIC PRESERVATION OFFICE NEW YORK CITY TRANSIT AUTHORITY REGARDING THE TIMES SQUARE SHUTTLE STATION DURING CONTRACT A- 35302, THE RECONFIGURATION OF THE TIMES SQUARE SHUTTLE STATION, SHPO PROJECT #17PR00545. |date=April 25, 2018 |website=mta.info |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe construction contract for the project was originally scheduled to be awarded in June 2018. However, this was delayed by several months because of changes to the project schedule and cost. The construction duration was expected to be extended by three months, and the cost would increase by $25 million, because of additions to the original construction plan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/180924_1400_CPOC.pdf |title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting - September 2018 |last= |first= |date=September 24, 2018 |website=mta.info |publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|access-date=September 23, 2018 |page=73}}</ref> A construction contract was awarded in March 2019, with an estimated completion date of March 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/190325_1400_CPOC.pdf |title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting - March 2019 |last= |first= |date=March 25, 2019 |website=mta.info |publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|access-date=September 23, 2018 |page=11}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = center\n | direction = horizontal\n | total_width = 1000\n | image1 = Times Sq-42nd St td 18 - IRT Shuttle.jpg\n | caption1 = Track 1 platform, looking toward connection to other two platforms\n | image2 = Times Square - 42nd Street - Shuttle Track 3.jpg\n | caption2 = Platform for track 3, with a train on that track\n | image3 = Times Sq-42 St shuttle platforms Apr 2018 06.jpg\n | caption3 = View from removable walkway over track 4, looking toward the Broadway&ndash;Seventh Avenue tunnel\n | image4 = Times Sq-42 St shuttle platforms Apr 2018 02.jpg\n | caption4 = Second and third cars of a train on track 4\n | image5 = Times Sq. Shuttle Plat. IRT At Track -4 Plat. Facing N. At Existing Station.jpg\n | caption5 = A view of the platform on Track 4 in 1958.\n}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==IND Eighth Avenue Line platforms==\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 42 Street\u2013<br/>&nbsp;Port Authority Bus Terminal\n| image = 42nd Street - Port Authority Bus Terminal - Downtown Platform.jpg\n| image_caption = Downtown platform.\n| accessible = yes\n| acc_note = passageway to other services not accessible\n| bg_color = #11117D\n| division = IND\n| line = [[IND Eighth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Eighth south\n| platforms = 2 [[island platform]]s<br />[[cross-platform interchange]] (upper level)<br/>1 abandoned [[side platform]] (lower level) \n| tracks = 4 (upper level)<br/>1 (lower level)\n| levels = 2 (lower level demolished)\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1932|09|10}}<ref name=Chambers>''[[The New York Times]]'', List of the 28 Stations on the New Eighth Ave Line, September 10, 1932, page 6</ref> (upper level)<br />{{start date and age|1952|08|25}}<ref name=NYTimes-42PABTLwrLvl-1952 /> (lower level)\n| close_date = 1981 (lower level)\n| code = 163\n| wifi = yes\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | type=express | line=IND Eighth Avenue Line | station=59th Street\u2013Columbus Circle | service=Eighth 50th express}}<br />{{NYCS next | type=local | line=IND Eighth Avenue Line | station=50th Street | service=Eighth 50th local}}<br />{{NYCS next | type=Queens Boulevard | station=50th Street | line=IND Queens Boulevard Line | service=Queens 53rd west}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=34th Street\u2013Penn Station | line=IND Eighth Avenue Line | service=Eighth south}}\n| next_north_acc = {{NYCS next | type=8th Ave | line=IND Eighth Avenue Line | station=59th Street\u2013Columbus Circle | service=Eighth 50th}}<br />{{NYCS next | type=Queens Boulevard | station=Lexington Avenue\u201353rd Street | line=IND Queens Boulevard Line | service=Queens 53rd west}}\n| next_south_acc = {{NYCS next | station=34th Street\u2013Penn Station | line=IND Eighth Avenue Line | service=Eighth south}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}\n}}\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{Routemap\n|title=Track layout\n|title-bg=#{{NYCS color|Eighth}}\n|legend =track\n|map=\nnumN330\nuvSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[59th Street\u2013Columbus Circle (IND Eighth Avenue Line)|59 St\u2013Columbus Cir]]\nudSTR!~dMFADEg\\uvSTR\\udSTR!~dMFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[50th Street (IND Eighth Avenue Line)|50 St]] lower level\nudSTR!~dMFADEg\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\udSTR!~dMFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[50th Street (IND Eighth Avenue Line)|50 St]] upper level \nuvSTRf\\uvSTRfg\\uvSTRg \nudSHI2g+l\\udSHI2glr\\udSHI2g+r\\udSHI2g+l\\udSHI2lr\\udSHI2g+r\nd\\udSTR\\udENDExe\\uvSTR\\d\\uvSHI2l-\nd\\uxvSTR\\uvSTR\\BS\\udSTR\nd\\uxvSTR\\uvSTR\\BS\\udSTR\nd\\uxvSTR\\uvSTR\\BS\\udSTR\nuv-STR\\uexdSTR!~dMFADEf\\uvSTR\\BS\\udSTR ~~ ~~ ~~ to former lower level\nuv-STR\\dBS\\uvSHI2l\\udSHI2+r\\dBS\\udSTR\nuv-STR\\BS\\udSTR\\udSTR\\uv-SHI2r\nudSTR\\BS\\udSTR\\uvSTR\nudSTR\\BS\\udSTR\\uvSTR\nudSTR\\BS\\udSTR\\uvSTR\nudSTR\\uexdSTR!~dMFADEg\\uvSHI2+l\\uvSHI2r ~~ ~~ ~~ from former lower level\nudSHI2l\\uxdSHI2gxl+r\\uedSHI2g+r\\uvSTR\\d\nuvSTRf\\uvSTRg\nuvSTR!~MFADEf\\uvSTR!~MFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[34th Street\u2013Penn Station (IND Eighth Avenue Line)|34 St\u2013Penn Sta]]\n}}\n[[File:NYCS IND WallTileScheme.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Wall mosaics]]\n}}\n\n'''42nd Street\u2013Port Authority Bus Terminal''' is an express [[metro station|station]] on the [[IND Eighth Avenue Line]]. It is partly underneath the [[Port Authority Bus Terminal]]. It has one platform level, two offset [[island platforms]], and a long mezzanine. Formerly, it also had a lower level with a single [[side platform]]. The upper level opened on September 10, 1932,<ref name=Chambers/><ref name=\"Opening\">{{cite news |last1=Crowell |first1=Paul |title=Gay Midnight Crowd Rides First Trains In The New Subway: Throngs at Station an Hour Before Time, Rush Turnstiles When Chains are Dropped |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1932/09/10/100849529.pdf |accessdate=November 8, 2015 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 10, 1932}}</ref> and the lower level opened on August 25, 1952.<ref name=NYTimes-42PABTLwrLvl-1952 />\n\n=== Platform level ===\nThe platform level of the station contains four tracks and two wide offset [[island platform]]s; the northbound platform extends from 42nd to 44th Streets, while the southbound platform extends from 40th to 42nd Streets. Unique to the Subway systems, [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA access]] is provided by passageway ramps. The station's mezzanine extends four blocks from 40th to 44th Streets, and connects with the rest of the complex by a long passageway underneath 41st Street.<ref name=MTA-TimesSquare-2015>{{cite web |title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Pennsylvania Station/Times Square |url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/mn/M08_PennStation_2015.pdf |website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]] |publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] |accessdate=December 11, 2015 |date=2015}}</ref><ref name=\"nycsubway.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Station:_42nd_Street-Port_Authority_Bus_Terminal_%288th_Avenue%29 |title=Station: 42nd Street-Port Authority Bus Terminal (8th Avenue) |accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Former lower level ===\nIn addition to the level currently in use, there was formerly a lower platform on the southbound side (one track underneath the downtown local track on the upper level, and one side platform underneath the island platform above). The lower level was built together with the upper level platforms in the late 1920s/early 1930s, but existed as an unfinished shell until it was completed<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yQwxAAAAMAAJ&dq=editions:UOM39015057041215&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=queens+line |title=Proceedings |last=Transportation |first=New York (N Y. ) Board of |date=1953 |language=en}}</ref>{{Rp|484}} and opened in August 1952 to serve rush hour {{NYCS|E}} trains.<ref name=NYTimes-42PABTLwrLvl-1952>{{cite web |title=New IND Platform Will Open Monday |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1952/08/23/84347733.pdf |website=[[The New York Times|nytimes.com]] |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=June 30, 2015 |date=August 23, 1952}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes-42PABTLwr-Expedite-1952 /> For most of its existence, the lower level platform was only used for occasional service specials, including summer \"Rockaway Special\" trains to [[Beach 98th Street (IND Rockaway Line)|Beach 98th Street]] at the [[Rockaways' Playland]] beginning in 1958, the [[Aqueduct Racetrack (IND Rockaway Line)|Aqueduct Racetrack]] special fare trains from 1959 to 1981, and rush hour E trains in the 1970s, beginning on March 23, 1970.<ref name=\"NYT2008\">{{cite news |first=Alex |last=Mindlin |title=No Whoosh, No \u2018All Aboard\u2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/20/nyregion/thecity/20port.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 20, 2008 |accessdate=July 10, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"SASblog2008\">{{cite web |url=http://secondavenuesagas.com/2008/04/21/with-the-7-on-the-way-a-swan-song-for-a-times-square-platform/ |title=With the 7 on the way, a swan song for a Times Square platform |last=Kabak |first=Benjamin |date=April 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.columbia.edu/~brennan/abandoned/42st.html |title=Abandoned Stations: 42 St Lower Level |first=Joseph |last=Brennan |year=2002 |accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Non-Stop Trips, Reserved Seats On Special Here: Deluxe Subway Express Ride Also Features Music; $1.55 Round-Trip Fare From 42nd Street To Playland Station Provides Admission And Rides |url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/viewer/?file=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspapers%252021%2FRockaway%2520Beach%2520NY%2520%2520Wave%2520Of%2520Long%2520Island%2FRockaway%2520Beach%2520NY%2520%2520Wave%2520Of%2520Long%2520Island%2520%25201958%2FRockaway%2520Beach%2520NY%2520%2520Wave%2520Of%2520Long%2520Island%2520%25201958%2520-%25200286.pdf&highlightsFile=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2Fhighlighter%2Fhits%2F652bb2fd7e9ec6c4f0e39d15f1b10cf5#page=1 |accessdate=August 17, 2016 |work=[[Wave of Long Island]] |agency=[[Fultonhistory.com]] |date=July 3, 1958 |page=1}}</ref>\n\nThe lower level featured two high-speed escalators to the mezzanine, and three staircases to the upper-level platform. The walls featured 1950s-era cream tiles, a purple and black tile band, and white mosaic name plates with black \"42ND ST\" text.<ref name=NYTimes-42PABTLwrLvl-1952/><ref name=NYTimes-42PABTLwr-Expedite-1952>{{cite web |last1=Ingraham |first1=Joseph C. |title=New IND Platform at 8th and 42d To Expedite Service From Queens |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1952/06/20/93496604.pdf |website=[[The New York Times|nytimes.com]] |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=June 30, 2015 |date=June 20, 1952}}</ref><ref name=NYT2008 />\n\nTheories differ on why the lower level platform was built. The platform could only be reached by trains originating from [[Queens]] via the [[IND Queens Boulevard Line]], and 53rd Street (the current E service).  Some commentators have speculated that this was meant to allow Manhattan-bound E trains from Queens to hold at 42nd Street without slowing down service on trains traveling from Central Park West,<ref name=\"SASblog2008\" /> while the reported purpose of the platform upon its opening was to allow E trains to load and unload passengers without having to wait for one of the two upper level tracks to clear.<ref name=NYTimes-42PABTLwrLvl-1952 /><ref name=NYTimes-42PABTLwr-Expedite-1952 />  Others have suggested that the lower level platform was built to prevent the [[IRT Flushing Line]] from being extended westward.  The IND lower level platform was located just beyond the tail tracks on the IRT Flushing Line platform.<ref name=\"nycsubway.org\" /><ref name=\"SASblog2008\" /><ref name=\"flickr2013\">{{cite web |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/benyankee/11468884304/in/set-72157638861830194/ |title=7 Line Extension 081 |work=Flickr}}</ref>\n\nFilm producers have used the lower level platform for several films, most notably ''[[Ghost (1990 film)|Ghost]]'' (1990), starring [[Patrick Swayze]] and [[Demi Moore]].<ref name=\"NYT2008\" /><ref name=\"SASblog2008\" />\n\t\nIn the late 2000s, the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]] began construction on a planned [[7 Subway Extension|extension of the IRT Flushing Line]] to [[34th Street\u2013Hudson Yards (IRT Flushing Line)|34th Street]], which would require demolishing the IND Eighth Avenue lower level platform.<ref name=\"SASblog2008\" /> {{As of|2010|1}}, the lower level platform was being demolished as part of the Flushing Line extension.<ref>{{cite news |title=Abandoned No More: 2nd Life Drilled into Old 7 Subway Platform |first=Pete |last=Donohue |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2009/06/20/2009-06-20_abandoned_no_more_2nd_life_drilled_into_old_7_subway_platform.html |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |date=June 20, 2009 |accessdate=January 30, 2010}}</ref> Transit blogger Benjamin Kabak, who was invited to tour the Flushing Line extension and view construction progress, reported in February 2012 that the lower level platform had been \"bisected\" by the Flushing Line extension.<ref name=\"SASblog2012\">{{cite web |url=http://secondavenuesagas.com/2012/02/12/photos-inside-the-7-line-extension/ |title=Photos: Inside the 7 line extension |last=Kabak |first=Benjamin |date=February 12, 2012 |accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref> The tunnels slope down through where the old lower level platform was.<ref name=\"flickr2013\"/>\n\n[[File:Times Sq-42nd St td 36 - Passageway.jpg|thumb|left|A sign at the western end of the passageway ramp, informing customers that the passageway to rest of the complex is not wheelchair accessible]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== {{anchor|IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line platforms}}IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line platforms ==\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = Times Square\u201342 Street\n| accessible = yes\n| acc_note = Transfer accessible to [[#BMT Broadway Line platforms|BMT Broadway Line]] and [[#IRT Flushing Line platform|IRT Flushing Line]] platforms only\n| bg_color = #E20F00\n| image = Times Square-42nd Street (Broadway-Seventh Avenue Line).jpg\n| image_caption = Downtown platform\n| division = IRT\n| line = [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]]\n| service = Broadway-Seventh\n| platforms = 2 [[island platform]]s<br>[[cross-platform interchange]]\n| tracks = 4\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1917|06|03}}<ref name=34th/>\n| rebuilt = 1998-2002\n| code = 317\n| wifi = yes\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | type=express | line=IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line | station=72nd Street | service=Broadway-Seventh center express}}<br>{{NYCS next | type=local | line=IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line | station=50th Street | service=Broadway-Seventh center local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next|service=Times Square IRT terminal night|terminal=(Terminal)|time=show}}<br>{{NYCS next | station=34th Street\u2013Penn Station | line=IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line | service=Broadway-Seventh center south}}\n| next_north_acc = {{NYCS next | type=express | line=IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line | station=72nd Street | service=Broadway-Seventh center express}}<br>{{NYCS next | type=local | line=IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line | station=59th Street\u2013Columbus Circle | service=Broadway-Seventh center local}}\n| next_south_acc = {{NYCS next|service=Times Square IRT terminal night|terminal=none|time=show}}<br>{{NYCS next | station=34th Street\u2013Penn Station | line=IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line | service=Broadway-Seventh center south}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}\n}}\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{Routemap\n|title=Track layout\n|title-bg=#{{NYCS color|red}}\n|legend =track\n|map=\nuvSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[72nd Street (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|72 St]]\nudSTR!~dMFADEg\\uvSTR\\udSTR!~dMFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[50th Street (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|50 St]]\n\\uvSTR\\uvSTR-ABZg2\\uSTRc3\nnumN330\\uvSTRf\\uvSTRg!~uSTRc1\\uSTR2+4!~MFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[Times Square\u201342nd Street/Port Authority Bus Terminal (New York City Subway)#IRT 42nd Street Shuttle platforms|shuttle platforms]]\nuv-SHI2r\\uvSTR\\uvSHI2l-\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nudSTR\\dBS\\uvSTR\\dBS\\udSTR\nuvSHI2l-\\uvSTR\\uv-SHI2r\nuSHI1c2\\uvSPLa\\uvSPLa\\uSHI1c3\nuvSTR\\uvSTR!~uSTRc2\\udABZg3\nuvSTR\\uvABZg+1-!~uv-STR\\udSTR!~udSTRc4\nuvSTRf\\udSTR\\uvSTRg\nuvSTR!~MFADEf\\udSTR!~dMFADEf\\uvSTR!~MFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[34th Street\u2013Penn Station (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|34 St\u2013Penn Sta]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Times Square\u201342nd Street''' is an express station on the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]], with four tracks and two [[island platform]]s. Access to the other lines is provided at the northern end and in the center of each platform. An elevator leads from each platform to the mezzanine; the southbound elevator also leads to the Flushing Line platform.\n\nJust south of the station, a fifth center track begins, formed by a connection from each express track. This track merges back into the two express tracks just before [[34th Street\u2013Penn Station (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|34th Street\u2013Penn Station]].<ref>{{NYCS const|trackref|468}}</ref> This center track was used in the past for turning rush hour \"Gap Trains\", which would head back up north. It is currently used for [[short turn]]ing 3 trains during nights.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Service Enhancements on 3 Line |publisher=MTA New York City Transit |date=July 24, 2008 |url=http://www.mta.info/mta/news/releases/?en=080724-NYCT109 |accessdate=July 26, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===History===\nThe station opened on June 3, 1917, as part of an extension of the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]], the dominant subway in [[Manhattan]] at the time, to [[South Ferry loops (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|South Ferry]].<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=New York Times |title=Three New Links of the Dual Subway System Opened |date=June 3, 1917 |page=33}}</ref> It was served by a shuttle train to 34th Street\u2013Penn Station until the rest of the extension opened a year later on July 1, 1918.<ref name=\"west side open\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1918/07/02/archives/open-new-subway-to-regular-traffic-first-train-on-seventh-avenue.html |title=Open new subway to regular traffic |newspaper=New York Times |accessdate=August 27, 2008}}</ref> This meant that the subway would be expanded down the Lower West Side to neighborhoods such as [[Greenwich Village]] and the western portion of the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]].\n\nAs part of this and the northern [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] extension, the IRT network would be radically changed from an S-shaped line connecting the eastern side of Lower Manhattan to the [[Upper West Side]] to an H-shaped network with two parallel lines, the East and West Side Lines, and the current shuttle at 42nd Street connecting them.<ref name=\"west side open\"/><ref name=\"east side open\">{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1918/08/02/97011929.pdf |title=Open new subway lines to traffic; called a triumph |newspaper=New York Times |accessdate=August 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThis section was the site of a [[Times Square derailment|1928 wreck]] that killed 16 people, the second worst in New York City history (the worst being the [[Malbone Street Wreck]] in Brooklyn, which killed at least 93).\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== BMT Broadway Line platforms ==\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = Times Square\u201342 Street\n| accessible = yes\n| acc_note = Transfer accessible to [[#IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line platforms|IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] &amp; [[#IRT Flushing Line platform|IRT Flushing Line]] platforms only\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = black\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| image = Times Sq-42nd St td 37 - BMT Broadway.jpg\n| image_caption = Uptown platform\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Broadway Line]]\n| service = Broadway Seventh\n| platforms = 2 [[island platform]]s<br>[[cross-platform interchange]]\n| tracks = 4\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1918|01|05}}<ref name=42nd>''[[The New York Times]]'', [http://www.nycsubway.org/articles/nytimes-1918-broadway.html Open New Subway to Times Square], January 6, 1918</ref>\n| code = 011\n| wifi = yes\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | type=express | line=BMT Broadway Line | station=57th Street\u2013Seventh Avenue | service=Broadway Seventh express}}<br>{{NYCS next | type=local | line=BMT Broadway Line | station=49th Street | service=Broadway Seventh local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=34th Street\u2013Herald Square | line=BMT Broadway Line | service=Broadway}}\n| next_north_acc = {{NYCS next | station=Lexington Avenue\u201363rd Street | line=BMT 63rd Street Line | service=63rd BMT}}<br>{{NYCS next | line=BMT Broadway Line | station=49th Street | service=Broadway Seventh local}} (northbound only; via local)\n| next_south_acc = {{NYCS next | station=34th Street\u2013Herald Square | line=BMT Broadway Line | service=Broadway}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}{{NYCS infobox legend|weekdaysonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|weekendsonly}}\n}}\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked express station\n|1=49th Street\n|l1=49 St\n|2=34th Street\u2013Herald Square\n|l2=34 St\n|3=57th Street\u2013Seventh Avenue\n|l3=57 St\n|4=34th Street\u2013Herald Square\n|l4=34 St\n|code=BMT Broadway Line\n|color=Broadway\n|deg=330\n}}\n}}\n'''Times Square\u201342nd Street''' is an express station on the [[BMT Broadway Line]] that has four tracks and two [[island platform]]s. Connections to the other lines are at the northern end of the platforms.\n\nThe express tracks north of the station spread out to pass around a crossunder in the Times Square shuttle platforms. This crossunder was sealed off in the 1960s.\n\n=== History ===\nOn February 8, 1914, the Public Service Commission ordered Chief Engineer Craven to make this station an express station as opposed to a local station as originally planned. The change was made at the insistence of Brooklynites who wanted an express station in the theater section of Manhattan. Under the original plan, the express stop would have been located at 47th Street, with a local stop at 42nd. The stop, as an express station, was planned to have connections to the IRT shuttle platforms, the Steinway tunnel line, and the IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1914/02/08/archives/42d-street-an-express-stop-a-big-victory-for-brooklynites-says-the.html |title=42D STREET AN EXPRESS STOP.; A Big Victory for Brooklynites, Says The Brooklyn Eagle. |last=Eagle |first=From The Brooklyn |date=February 8, 1914 |work=The New York Times|access-date=August 1, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn June 1, 1940, the title of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] was transferred to the [[New York City|City of New York]], signifying the first phase of unification of New York's subway system with the [[Independent Subway System]] as well as eventual public operation of the entire system. (The [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] would be merged on June 15 of the same year.) At midnight, a ceremony commemorating the transfer, with five hundred people in attendance, was held at the Times Square station. The last BMT train had left the [[57th Street\u2013Seventh Avenue (BMT Broadway Line)|57th Street]] station five minutes earlier. When the train arrived at Times Square, BMT president William S. Menden handed over his company's properties to Mayor [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia]], who then gave them to [[New York City Board of Transportation]] chairman John H. Delaney. The Board of Transportation operated the [[New York City Transit System]] until the creation of the [[New York City Transit Authority]] in 1953.<ref>{{cite book |first=Clifton |last=Hood |title=722 Miles: The Building of the Subways and How They Transformed New York |year=2004 |edition=Centennial |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press |isbn=0-8018-8054-8 |pages=238\u2013239}}</ref>\n\nThis station received a minor overhaul in the late 1970s when [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]] fixed the station's structure and the overall appearance, and it repaired staircases and platform edges, removed pedestrian ramps, and replaced lighting.\n\nIn 2004-2006, the station received a major overhaul and repairs, including upgrading the station for [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA compliance]] and restoring the original late 1910s tiling. MTA repaired the staircases, retiled the walls, added new tiling on the floors, upgraded the station's lights and the public address system, installed [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA]] yellow safety treads along the platform edge, and installed new signs and new trackbeds in both directions.\n\n[[File:Times Square NYC subway 010.JPG|thumb|left|\"42\" monogram mosaic]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== IRT Flushing Line platform ==\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = Times Square\u201342 Street\n| accessible = yes\n| acc_note = Transfer accessible to [[#IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line platforms|IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] and [[#BMT Broadway Line platforms|BMT Broadway Line]] platforms only\n| image = Times Square - 42nd Street - Flushing Line Platform.jpg\n| image_caption = The IRT Flushing Line platform\n| font_color = white\n| bg_color = purple\n| division = IRT\n| line = [[IRT Flushing Line]]\n| service = Flushing south\n| platforms = 1 [[island platform]]\n| tracks = 2\n| structure = Underground\n<!--| former = Seventh Avenue-->\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1927|03|14}}<ref name=\"FlushingtoTimes\">''[[The New York Times]]'', [https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0A14F73E5B157A93C7A81788D85F438285F9 New Queens Subway Opened to Times Sq.], March 15, 1927, page 1</ref>\n| code = 467\n| wifi = yes\n| next_east = {{NYCS next | station=Fifth Avenue | line=IRT Flushing Line | service=Flushing south}}\n| next_west = {{NYCS next | station=10th Avenue | line=IRT Flushing Line | service=Flushing future}}<br>{{NYCS next | station=34th Street\u2013Hudson Yards | line=IRT Flushing Line | service=Flushing south}}\n| next_east_acc = {{NYCS next | station=Grand Central\u201342nd Street | line=IRT Flushing Line | service=Flushing south}}\n| next_west_acc = {{NYCS next | station=10th Avenue | line=IRT Flushing Line | service=Flushing future}}<br>{{NYCS next | station=34th Street\u2013Hudson Yards | line=IRT Flushing Line | service=Flushing south}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{Routemap\n|title=Track layout\n|title-bg=#{{NYCS color|Flushing}}\n|legend =track\n|map=\nnumN240\\uvSTR!~MFADEg\\ ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[Fifth Avenue (IRT Flushing Line)|5 Av]]\nuvSTRfg\nuv\u00dcST\nuSHI1+l\\uSHI1+r\nuSTR+BSl\\uSTR+BSr\nuSTR+BSl\\uSTR+BSr\nuSTR+BSl\\uSTR+BSr\nuSTR+BSl\\uSTR+BSr\nuSHI1l\\uSHI1r\nuvSTRfg\nuvSTR!~MFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[34th Street\u2013Hudson Yards (IRT Flushing Line)|34 St]]\n}}\n[[File:Queensboro Subway Service Extended To Times Square Station 1927.jpg|thumb|Queensboro Subway Service Extended To Times Square station 1927]]\n}}\n\n'''Times Square\u201342nd Street''' on the [[IRT Flushing Line]] has one [[island platform]] and two tracks, located deep below West 41st Street.\n\n=== History ===\nThe Times Square station opened on March 14, 1927, extending the Flushing Line westward from its previous terminus at Fifth Avenue.<ref name=\"nyt-1927-03-15\">{{cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0A14F73E5B157A93C7A81788D85F438285F9 |title=New Queens Subway Opened to Times Sq. |date=March 15, 1927 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=1 |accessdate=October 2, 2011}}</ref> This station served as the terminus for {{NYCS Flushing south}} trains from its opening on March 14, 1927, until September 13, 2015, when the next station west ([[Railroad direction|railroad south]]), [[34th Street\u2013Hudson Yards (IRT Flushing Line)|34th Street\u2013Hudson Yards]], opened.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/capital/no7_alt.html |title=New 34 St-Hudson Yards '''7''' Station Opens |publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|Metropolitan Transit Authority]] |location=New York, New York |quote=The new station opened September 13, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304003930/http://web.mta.info/capital/no7_alt.html |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |accessdate=March 10, 2016 |work=Building for the Future}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web |url=http://web.mta.info/nyct/service/7_timesSq_Sep15.htm |title=7 subway service is now running to/from the new 34 St-Hudson Yards station. Times Sq-42 St is no longer the Manhattan terminal. At Times Sq-42 St, Queens-bound express and local service leave from Track 2 only. |last= |first= |date=September 2015 |website=mta.info |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=December 18, 2016}}</ref> The platforms at Times Square and all other stations on the Flushing Line with the exception of [[Queensboro Plaza (New York City Subway)|Queensboro Plaza]] were extended in 1955\u20131956 to accommodate 11-car trains.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MrAjAQAAMAAJ&dq=dyre+avenue+line&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22main+street%22 |title=Minutes and Proceedings |last=Authority |first=New York City Transit |date=1955 |publisher= |year= |isbn= |location= |pages= |language=en |via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Layout ===\nStairs, escalators, and an elevator along the platform lead to various mezzanines. There are \"TS\" tile mosaics along the station walls. An office is located at the north (compass east) end of the platform. An elevator was recently installed and connects with the Downtown IRT Seventh Avenue platform and then the mezzanine. The elevators make this platform, along with the platform at [[Grand Central (IRT Flushing Line)|Grand Central]] accessible to wheelchair passengers (unlike the [[Times Square (IRT 42nd Street Shuttle)|shuttle platforms]], which are not accessible to wheelchairs).\n\nThe tracks continue south (compass west) beyond the station to the 34th Street station. These tracks formerly led to an unused storage and layover area, but the [[7 Subway Extension|extension of the Flushing Line]], whose trackwork was completed in 2013, included the addition of [[third rail]]s to the layover tracks, as well as the inspection and replacement of these tracks.<ref>{{cite web |title=View of Tunnel from station platform showing sign indicating no third rail power |url=http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/show?95602 |accessdate=April 1, 2009}}</ref> The closed lower level platform at [[42nd Street\u2013Port Authority Bus Terminal (IND Eighth Avenue Line)|42nd Street\u2013Port Authority Bus Terminal]] on the [[IND Eighth Avenue Line]] was blocking the line but since removed.<ref name=\"NYT2008\"/> Currently, all Flushing-bound service is on the eastbound track, labeled Track 2, and 34th Street-bound service is on the westbound track, labeled Track 1.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Artwork ==\n[[Heins and LaFarge|George Lewis Heins and Christopher Grant LaFarge]] were the first commissioned architects of the IRT. They designed the original Times Square Station, which was located at the current Grand Central Shuttle stop.\n\nIn many of their stations, Heins and LaFarge use symbolic imagery to honor a neighborhood or its namesake. When [[Squire Vickers]] took over as chief designer and architect of the IRT in 1906, he continued this tradition of using symbolism to speak to a station's history.\n\nThe colored tile trim of the IRT portions of the station closely resembles the [[Confederate flag]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historynet.com/confederate-flags-in-times-square.htm |title=Confederate Flags in Times Square? |work=History Net: Where History Comes Alive \u2013 World & US History Online}}</ref> Scholars believe that Vickers and his colleagues unmistakably reference the symbol of the South to pay homage to ''New York Times'' owner [[Adolph Ochs|Adolph S. Ochs]].<ref>Jackowe, David J. \"The Times Square Confederate.\" Civil War Times; Aug 2012, Vol. 51 Issue 4, p. 42. http://www.historynet.com/confederate-flags-in-times-square.htm</ref> The Confederacy was a significant part of Ochs' heritage, and the eccentric Vickers relished literary and historical imagery.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/03/arts/design/03subw.html Underground Renaissance Man: Watch the Aesthetic Walls, Please]</ref> After a 2010s movement in which Confederate monuments nationwide were removed, the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] announced in August 2017 that these tiles would be replaced;<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ny.curbed.com/2017/8/18/16166620/mta-times-square-subway-tile-modification |title=MTA will modify Times Square subway tile resembling a Confederate flag |last=Plitt |first=Amy |date=August 18, 2017 |website=Curbed NY|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/18/nyregion/mta-confederate-flag-tiles.html |title=M.T.A. to Modify Subway Station Design Resembling Confederate Flag |last=Stevens |first=Matt |date=August 18, 2017 |work=The New York Times|access-date=August 31, 2017 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the tiles were subsequently covered with stickers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Subway tiles that looked like Confederate flags in Times Square covered with stickers |website=amNewYork |date=August 24, 2017 |url=https://www.amny.com/transit/subway-tiles-that-looked-like-confederate-flags-in-times-square-covered-with-stickers-1-14087974/ | access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTimes Square was named for ''The New York Times'', whose [[One Times Square|headquarters]], built by Ochs, housed the original subway station (now the shuttle platforms) in its basement.<ref>{{cite book |last=McKendry |first=Joe |title=One Times Square: A Century of Change at the Crossroads of the World |url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=S1FfFwpp5Z4C&pg=PT10 |publisher=David R. Godine Publisher |date=2011 |pages=10\u201314 |isbn=9781567923643}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Crump |first=William D. |title=Encyclopedia of New Year's Holidays Worldwide |url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=ujTfCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA242 |publisher=McFarland |date=2014 |page=242 |isbn=9781476607481}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Barron |first=James |date=April 8, 2004 |title=100 Years Ago, an Intersection's New Name: Times Square |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/08/nyregion/100-years-ago-an-intersection-s-new-name-times-square.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151224120212/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/08/nyregion/100-years-ago-an-intersection-s-new-name-times-square.html?_r=0 |archive-date = December 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Times Square Confederate Mosaic - Original.jpg|Original colored tile trim, before the station renovation of the late 1990s. Scholars believe architect [[Squire J. Vickers]] used this design to pay homage to the Southern roots of former ''New York Times'' newspaper head [[Adolph S. Ochs]]\nFile:Times Square Confederate Mosaic - Modern Version.jpg|1998-recreated tiles, also to be removed\nFile:Lichtenstein Under Times Square vc.jpg|''[[Times Square Mural]]'' by [[Roy Lichtenstein]]\nFile:42nd Street artwork vc.jpg|''The Return of Spring/The Onset of Winter'' by Jack Beal\nFile:The Revelers vc.jpg|''The Revelers'' by [[Jane Dickson]]\nFile:New York in Transit vc.jpg|''New York in Transit'' by Jacob Lawrence\nFile:Times Square Times vc.jpg|''Times Square Times'' by Toby Buonagurio\nFile:Just Go Home 42 Street vc.jpg|''The Commuter's Lament'' by Norman B. Colp\n</gallery>\n\nModern artwork installed in the complex includes the following:\n\n*''The Commuter's Lament'' or ''A Close Shave'' by Norman B. Colp, 1991\n*''New York in Transit'' by [[Jacob Lawrence]], 2001\n* ''The Return of Spring''/''The Onset of Winter'' by Jack Beal, 2001/2005\n* ''[[Times Square Mural]]'' by [[Roy Lichtenstein]], 2002 (collage 1990, fabricated 1994)\n* ''Times Square Times: 35 Times'' by [[Toby Buonagurio]], 2005\n* ''The Revelers'' by Jane Dickson, 2008\n\n''New York in Transit'' was Lawrence's last public work before his 2000 death.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Times Square Subway Mural Unveiled |url=http://www.mta.info/mta/news/releases/index.html?agency=hq&en=011107 |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority |date=November 7, 2001 |accessdate=April 11, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605235752/http://www.mta.info/mta/news/releases/index.html?agency=hq&en=011107 |archivedate=June 5, 2011 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lichtenstein completed ''Times Square Mural'' in 1994, but installation was delayed until after the station complex's renovation, during which Lichtenstein died in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |title=Times Square Mural |url=http://www.lichtensteinfoundation.org/timesqmural.htm |author=Carol Vogel |work=The Roy Lichtenstein Foundation |accessdate=April 11, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100201042728/http://www.lichtensteinfoundation.org/timesqmural.htm |archivedate=February 1, 2010 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''The Commuter's Lament'' is a series of signs attached to the roof of the lower passageway, inspired by classic [[Burma-Shave]] ads. In order, the signs read ''Overslept/So tired/If late/Get fired/Why bother?/Why the pain?/Just go home/Do it again.''; The last panel is a picture of a bed. The panels were part of an art project that was supposed to last only one year, but were never removed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?185 |title=Artwork: \"The Commuter's Lament/A Close Shave\", Norman B. Colp (1991) |accessdate=October 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Terror plots ==\nThe Times Square station has been targeted by two failed terrorist plots:\n* In September 2009, [[Najibullah Zazi]] and alleged co-conspirators planned suicide bombings on subway trains near this station and the [[Grand Central\u201342nd Street (New York City Subway)#Foiled terrorist attack|Grand Central\u201342nd Street station]], but the plot was discovered before they could carry it out.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/nyregion/16terror.html?_r=1 |title=Man in Queens Raids Denies Any Terrorist Link |date=September 15, 2009 |first=Karen |last=Zraik |first2=David |last2=Johnston |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n* There was also an [[2017 New York City attempted bombing|attempted bombing]] on December 11, 2017, during the morning rush hour, when a [[pipe bomb]] device partially detonated in the passageway connecting the IND Eighth Avenue Line station with the rest of the complex.<ref>{{cite web |last=Griggs |first=Troy |last2=Lai |first2=K.K. Rebecca |last3=Wallace |first3=Tim |title=Where the Port Authority Subway Explosion Happened |website=The New York Times |date=2017-12-11 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/11/nyregion/port-authority-subway-explosion-maps.html}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Further reading ===\n*{{cite book |last=Stookey |first=Lee |title=Subway ceramics : a history and iconography of mosaic and bas relief signs and plaques in the New York City subway system |publisher=L. Stookey | publication-place=Brattleboro, Vt |year=1994 |isbn=978-0-9635486-1-0 |oclc=31901471}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Times Square \u2013 42nd Street / Port Authority Bus Terminal (New York City Subway)}}\n\n'''nycsubway.org:'''\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Station:_42nd_Street-Times_Square#IRT_Contract_One_.28Shuttle.29_Station IRT Grand Central/Times Square Shuttle: Times Square]\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/IRT_Flushing_Line#Times_Square IRT Flushing Line: Times Square]\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Station:_42nd_Street-Times_Square#IRT_West_Side_Line_Station IRT West Side Line: Times Square/42nd Street] (text used with permission)<!--given to [[User:PZFUN]]-->\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Station:_42nd_Street-Times_Square#BMT_Broadway_Line_Station BMT Broadway Subway: Times Square/42nd Street]\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Station:_42nd_Street-Port_Authority_Bus_Terminal_(8th_Avenue) IND Eighth Avenue Line: 42nd Street/Port Authority Bus Terminal]\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?27 New York in Transit Artwork by Jacob Lawrence (2001)]\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?36 Times Square Mural Artwork by Roy Lichtenstein (1994)]\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?110 The Return of Spring/The Onset of Winter Artwork by Jack Beal (1999)]\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?122 Times Square Times: 35 Times Artwork by Toby Buonagurio (2005)]\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?194 The Revelers Artwork by Jane Dickson (2007)]\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?109 Losing My Marbles Artwork by Lisa Dinhofer (2003)]\n* nycsubway.org \u2013 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?185 The Commuter's Lament/A Close Shave Artwork by Norman B. Colp (1991)]\n{{refend}}\n\n'''MTA Arts for Transit'''\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2013 [http://web.mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=A&station=3&xdev=123 42nd Street\u2013Port Authority Bus Terminal (IND Eighth Avenue Line)]\n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2013 [http://web.mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=1&station=13&xdev=1307 Times Square\u201342nd Street, Page 1]\n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2013 [http://web.mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=1&station=12&xdev=1142 Times Square\u201342nd Street, Page 2]\n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2013 [http://web.mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=A&station=3&xdev=123 42nd Street\u201