omen's 4 \u00d7 200 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7200 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2019 Gwangju|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 200 metre freestyle|200 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2017 World Aquatics Championships|2017 Budapest]]|[[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 200 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7200 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2019 Gwangju|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 800 metre freestyle|800 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|World Championships (SC)]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 Hangzhou]]|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 200 metre freestyle|200 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 400 metre freestyle|400 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 50 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d750 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2018 Hangzhou|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 200 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7200 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|Pan Pacific Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|2018 Tokyo]]|4\u00d7200 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalSilver|2018 Tokyo|400 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalSilver|2018 Tokyo|800 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]]|[[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 400 metre freestyle|400 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2018 Gold Coast|[[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 800 metre freestyle|800 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2018 Gold Coast|[[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 200 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7200 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2018 Gold Coast|[[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 200 metre freestyle|200 m freestyle]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Ariarne Titmus''' (born 7 September 2000) is an Australian [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]]. She currently represents the Cali Condors which is part of the [[International Swimming League]]. In 2015, Titmus and her family moved from [[Tasmania]] to [[Queensland]] for better training opportunities.<ref name=\"examiner\">{{cite web |last1=Shaw |first1=Rob |title=Titmus on move |url=http://www.examiner.com.au/story/3090536/titmus-on-move/ |website=[[The Examiner (Tasmania)|The Examiner]] |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> \nShe competed in the [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 200 metre freestyle|women's 200 metre freestyle]] event at the [[2017 World Aquatics Championships]].<ref name=\"WAC\">{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0201EE01FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |title=Heats results |accessdate=25 July 2017 |work=FINA |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930154648/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000111010A0201EE01FFFFFFFFFFFF01 |archive-date=30 September 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Budapest\">{{cite web |url=https://fina-budapest2017.com/en/home |title=2017 World Aquatics Championships > Search via Athletes |accessdate=25 July 2017 |work=Budapest 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===International Swimming League===\nIn 2019 she was a member of the inaugural [[International Swimming League]] representing the Cali Condors, who finished third place in the final match in Las Vegas, Nevada in December. Titmus won the 400 meter freestyle several times throughout the season including the final.  <ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/international-swimming-league-finale-in-las-vegas-day-two-live-recap/ |title=international-swimming-league-finale-in-las-vegas-day-two-live-recap |first1=Braden |last1=Keith |date=December 21, 2019 |publisher=[[SwimSwam]] }} </ref>\n\n===2018===\nAt the [[2018 Commonwealth Games]], Titmus won gold in the 4 x 200 meter freestyle event. On 14 December 2018 she set a new world record in the women's short course 400 meter freestyle competition of the [[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 400 metre freestyle|2018 FINA World Swimming Championships]] with a time of 3:53.92, breaking the record set by [[Wang Jianjiahe]] two months earlier by 0.05 seconds.\n\n===2019===\nTitmus was selected as one of the 27 swimmers to represent Australia at the [[2019 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Gwangju]], South Korea. After finishing second in her heat of the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 400 metre freestyle|women's 400 meter freestyle]], she won the gold medal and broke the [[List of Oceanian records in swimming|Oceania record]] in the final with a time of 3:58.76, a full second ahead of American swimmer [[Katie Ledecky]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-07-22/ariane-titmus-wins-gold-over-kate-ledecky-at-world-titles/11330076 |title=Ariarne Titmus claims gold in 400m freestyle over American swimming great Katie Ledecky |date=22 July 2019 |access-date=22 July 2019 |publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Swimming Australia|ariarne-titmus}} ([https://web.archive.org/web/20181215173426/https://www.swimming.org.au/Home/AustralianDolphins/AthleteProfile.aspx?AthleteID=86 archive])\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8PlZVovrhEA ''Ariarne Titmus interview ''].7 Sport (Video, 18 mins)\n\n{{Footer World LC Champions 400m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer World LC Champions 4x200m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 200m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 400m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer Pan Pacific Champions 4x200m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Footer Commonwealth Champions 4x200m Freestyle Women}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Titmus, Ariarne}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Australian female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Launceston, Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Sportswomen from Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2018 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:World Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian swimmer}}\n{{use Australian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Ariarne Titmus\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nickname       = Arnie, Terminator<ref name=\"GoldCoast\">{{cite web |title=Ariarne Titmus |url=https://results.gc2018.com/en/swimming/athlete-profile-n6029959-ariarne-titmus.htm |work=Athlete profile |publisher=Gold Coast 2018 |accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n| nationality    = Australian\n| strokes        = \n| club           = Cali Condors <br/> St Peters Western <ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/cali-condors-unveil-roster-for-2019-international-swimming-league-finale/ |title=cali-condors-unveil-roster-for-2019-international-swimming-league-finale |first1=Brademn |last1=Keith |date=December 9, 2019 |publisher=[[SwimSwam]] }} </ref>\n| collegeteam    = \n| coach          = Dean Boxall\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|2000|9|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Launceston, Tasmania]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Ariarne Titmus |url=https://www.swimming.org.au/Home/AustralianDolphins/AthleteProfile.aspx?AthleteID=86 |publisher=Swimming Australia |accessdate=28 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215173426/https://www.swimming.org.au/Home/AustralianDolphins/AthleteProfile.aspx?AthleteID=86 |archive-date=15 December 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = 177 cm<ref name=\"GoldCoast\"/>\n| weight         = 63 kg<r